# 2p_ctf_respawn_clean — host (RED) kills the client (BLUE) and the
# client respawns. Verifies the respawned body comes back clean —
# no lingering FX_STUMP, no persistent damage decals, no hit-flash.
# Pairs with 2p_ctf_respawn_clean.client.shot which captures the
# CLIENT's own view of its respawned local mech (the case my earlier
# `mid != local_mech_id` gate broke).

window 1280 720
out build/shots/net/host_ctf_respawn_clean
network host 24035
name HostRed

spawn_at 600 1100
peer_spawn 1 800 1100

aim 800 1070

contact_sheet sheet cols 4 cell 320 180

at 140 shot t140_round_start

# Kill client (mech_id 1) at tick 250 — direct mech_kill via debug
# directive, no projectiles. Mid-life dismember pre-arm: not needed,
# kill itself fires the FX_STUMP via mech_apply_damage's damage path?
# No — kill_peer skips apply_damage; it calls mech_kill directly so
# no dismemberment. To test FX persistence we need the body to have
# dismembered limbs. Skip dismember here — we still want to verify
# the simpler "respawn comes back at full HP, no decals from a
# previous lifetime's stray hits" promise.
at 250 kill_peer 1
at 260 shot t260_just_after_kill
at 320 shot t320_dead_ragdoll

# Pre-respawn — body still ragdolling.
at 425 shot t425_pre_respawn

# Respawn at tick 250 + 180 = 430. The client's mech rejoins the
# round at a fresh BLUE spawn. From the host's camera it'll be off
# the screen (camera follows HostRed), but the alive transition
# itself is what we assert via the log.
at 440 shot t440_post_respawn
at 470 shot t470_respawn_settled
at 600 shot t600_round_still_active

at 660 end
